OBJECTIVE: To identify different segments in the existing customers based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank using clustering algorithms and to provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

"Market" implies targeting new customers and upselling existing customers.

"Service" implies improving the bank's customer support services as they are currently perceived by the customer as poor.

****************************************************************************************************

Data Dictionary:

Sl_No: Primary key of the records
Customer Key: Customer identification number
Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

#Setting up a function to handle univariate EDA analysis using a histogram/boxplot.
def eda_analysis_hist(data,column, figsize=(12,7), kde=False, bins=None):
  #Creating the subplot.
  f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows=2, sharex=True, figsize=figsize)
  
  #Creating the boxplot
  sns.boxplot(data=data, x=column, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color='violet')
  #Creating the histogram with bin options
  sns.histplot(data=data, x=column, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, kde=kde) if bins else sns.histplot(
      data=data, x=column, ax=ax_hist2, kde=kde)

  #Showing mean value on the histogram
  ax_hist2.axvline(data[column].mean(), color='green', linestyle='--')
  ax_hist2.axvline(data[column].median(), color='black', linestyle='-')
  #Showing median on the boxplot
  ax_box2.axvline(data[column].median(), color='black', linestyle='-')

  print('0.25 quartile:',data[column].quantile(0.25),' ','median:', data[column].median(),'','0.75 quartile:', data[column].quantile(0.75))
In [ ]:
#Setting up a function to handle univariate EDA analysis using a countplot.
def eda_analysis_count(data,column):
  sns.countplot(data=data,x=column,order=data[column].value_counts().index)
  plt.title('Sorted')
  plt.show()
  sns.countplot(data=data,x=column)
  plt.title('Unsorted')
  plt.show()

plt.show()

Setting vmin=0.50, which makes the chart highlight only the very positive correlations:

"Total_Credit_Cards" and "Avg_Credit_Limit" have the highest positive correlation with a value of 0.61. This makes sense as more credit cards do add up allowing for a greater total credit limit.

"Total_Visits_Online" and "Avg_Credit_Limit" have the second highest positive correlations with a value of 0.55. This is not self explanatory and is an insight into customer habits. Those who visit the bank online tend to have higher credit limits.

Setting vmax=-0.5, which makes the chart highlight only the very negative correlations:

"Total_Calls_Made" and "Total_Credit_Cards" have the highest negative correlation with a value of -0.65. While this relationship is not a given, it can be explained. The more calls a customer makes to the bank, the more likely it is that they are having some sort of problem with that bank. If they are contantly having problems, the likelyhood of them doing a lot of business with that bank (for example having many credit cards) goes down rapidly.

"Total_Visits_Online" and "Total_Visits_Bank" have the second highest negative correlation with a value of -0.55. This makes sense as the more of a customer's business they do online the less there is a need to then come in person.

#Importing the necessary libraries for KMeans clustering.
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from scipy.stats import zscore
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist



    













In [ ]:



    


#Creating scaled data.
#Will not need to select specific columns as all are numeric and independent.
scaled_df = df.apply(zscore)



    













In [ ]:



    


#Creating an "Elbow Plot" to narrow down the optimal value of "K".
#Creating a list where the variances will be storred.
variances = []

#Using the pairplot it was found that roughly 3 clusters would be needed. However, general practice suggests that we try at least 10 clusters.
clusters = range(1,11)

#Setting up a "for" loop to test each cluster value.
for k in clusters:
  model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
  model.fit(scaled_df)
  prediciton = model.predict(scaled_df)
  variances.append(sum(np.min(cdist(scaled_df,model.cluster_centers_,'euclidean'), axis=1)) / scaled_df.shape[0])

#Graphing the results of the search.
plt.plot(clusters, variances, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('K')
plt.ylabel('Variance')
plt.title('Elbow Method "K" Selection')



    















    
Out[ ]:








Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Elbow Method "K" Selection')










    




























From the above graph we can see that there is a sharp turn at "3". However, I will also try "4" as there can be an argument made for it as well and in general adding a value or two for comparison of silhouette scores is a good idea.













In [ ]:



    


#Checking silhouette scores for 3,4, and one value to the side of each for comparison.
#Chose 7 (technically 6) as top of range so that the graph comes out cleaner.
sil_scores = []
clusters2 = range(2,7)

for n in clusters2:
  model = KMeans(n_clusters=n, random_state=1)
  model.fit(scaled_df)
  prediction2 = model.predict(scaled_df)
  score = silhouette_score(scaled_df,prediction2)
  sil_scores.append(score)
  print('For n_clusters = {}, the silhouette score is {}'.format(n,score))

plt.plot(clusters2, sil_scores)
plt.title('Silhouette Scores')



    















    






For n_clusters = 2, the silhouette score is 0.41842496663215445
For n_clusters = 3, the silhouette score is 0.5157182558881063
For n_clusters = 4, the silhouette score is 0.3556670619372605
For n_clusters = 5, the silhouette score is 0.2717470361089752
For n_clusters = 6, the silhouette score is 0.255906765297388










    
Out[ ]:








Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Silhouette Scores')










    




























"3" has the highest silhouette score by far and as such will be the value used.

Method Comparisons















Both in KMeans and H clustering cluster "2" represents customers who are happy with the bank's servies as shown by the high amount of credit cards and high credit limit. Cluster "1" in H-Clustering coresponds to cluster "0" in KMeans and, as a reminder, this catergory is full of customers who seem to be unhappy with the bank. Clusters "1" in KMeans and "0" in H-Cluster are customers who don't have any outstanding qualities in their relationship with the bank besides their tendency to visit the bank in person more than the other two and visit the bank less online, again, more than the other two.

BUSINESS RECOMMENDATIONS:















Customers in label "1" are the ones most in need of quality customer serivce. They hold relatively few credit cards and have relatively low average credit limit while having the highest amount of calls made to the bank. This inidcates that they are very wary of entrusting their money to the bank due to the many issues they call about (no one calls when things are going well to congratulate the bank, they call when there is a problem). I would recommend focusing on placing extra effort to address the greivances of these customers. They make up (224/660) roughly a third of the customer base which means that if the bank can satisfy their complaints then it is potentially looking at a 34% increase in business, a very captivaing prospect.




Customers in label "2" are the ones that are satisfied with the banks services as represented by the low amount of phone calls made. They are the ones that account for most of the banks revenue as they have the highest amount of credit cards and highest average credit limit; indicating that they likely spend the most one way or another (either directly via credit card or though other means such as a loan). I recommend targeting this group of customers for promotions and upsells if applicable (also don't forget customer appreciation :). For example, emailing birthday wished, aniversaries, and "extra" good deals when savings options are given such as during a 4th of july or black friday/cyber monday sale). When that promotion is delivered, it is very important that it is delivered over the internet and not by mail or in-person. This is because customers in this group overwhelmingly visit the store online to such a degree that in-person visits are practically 0.




Customers in label "0" are not as monetarily invovled with the bank as customers from label "2" but are overall satisfied customers. They have, on average, few calls made, a pretty high number of credit cards, and a credit limit that is on the lower end of about thirty eight thousand. The one outstanding trait about these customers is their tendancy to visit the bank in-person and almost never online. As such, my recommendations are that these customers also be given promotions, upsells, and appreciations but adjusted for the amount of spending power they keep in the bank. However, this time these promotions need to be delivered either by mail or in-person and not via the internet.
